Both soldier's letters as well as some civilian post exists from march after the relief, going through
the normal civilian posts, probably via Natal to England. With the large relief force and obviously everyone wanting
to communicate with their relatives and friends a shortage of stamps appears to have been experienced. Some
of the letters are known marked _no stamps available_. On arrival they were taxed, but overstruck and delivered free. 









